The individual was not fighting for breath.
The main reason for the assessment was not an allergic reaction, heart attack, chest/upper back pain, probable stroke, recent fit/seizure or suicide attempt.
The main reason for contact was not new confusion, declared diabetic hypo/hyperglycaemia, or ICD shock.
The skin on the torso felt normal, warm or hot.
Pathway selected - Difficulty Passing Urine
The individual was able to carry out most or all normal activities.
There was no new loss of bowel control or leg movement and no saddle or lower limb paraesthesia.
There was no inability to pass urine over the last 12 hours.
There was no new or worsening confusion.
Breathing harder or faster when doing nothing was not described.
There was no spinal pain.
The pain was not getting worse.
There was no fever at the time of assessment or within the previous 12 hours.
The individual had not experienced a back injury within the previous 4 weeks.
Medication type or dosage had not changed within the previous 2 weeks.
User comment - 'Urgent Treatment Centre - Same Day Health Centre - Fleetwood'
Advice Given:
Unless advised not to, paracetamol may be used to relieve pain or fever. Follow the instructions in the pack. If in doubt ask a pharmacist.
